⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Question 79/120 – from_json()

🎤 Interview Question

You receive employee information as a JSON string.

Write PySpark code to parse it into structured columns.


---

📊 Input Dataset

emp_id	employee_json

101	{"name":"John","salary":60000}
102	{"name":"Alice","salary":70000}



---

✅ Expected Output

emp_id	employee

101	{John,60000}
102	{Alice,70000}



---

✅ Recommended Solution

from pyspark.sql.functions import from_json, col
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType

schema = StructType([
    StructField("name", StringType()),
    StructField("salary", IntegerType())
])

df = df.withColumn(
    "employee",
    from_json(col("employee_json"), schema)
)

df.show(truncate=False)


---

🎤 Most Asked Interview Questions

Q1. Why is a schema required?

Answer

from_json() needs a schema to interpret the JSON string and convert it into structured data.


---

Q2. What happens if the JSON doesn't match the schema?

Answer

Missing or incompatible fields are returned as NULL, and type mismatches may cause parsing issues depending on the data.


---

Q3. Where is from_json() used?

Answer

Kafka streams

REST API responses

Event data

Log processing



